    "jays": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Blue Jays",
      "league": "MLB",
      "record": "6&ndash;9",
      "detail": "4th in AL East &middot; 50th Anniversary Season &middot; Defending AL Champions",
      "live_strip": null,
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "The Blue Jays are caught in quicksand&mdash;swept by Washington, losers of four straight series, and now trudging into Milwaukee at 7-9 with their roster looking like a medical chart. <strong>Christian Yelich&rsquo;s groin injury has landed another pillar on the shelf</strong>, joining Jackson Chourio and Andrew Vaughn in the casualty ward at precisely the moment this team can least afford it.[1] Yet there&rsquo;s a strange mercy in tonight&rsquo;s matchup: the Brewers are drowning worse, six games down with their own roster in tatters.[1] Vladimir Guerrero Jr. remains the engine&mdash;13 hits over the last ten games, a .342 average that whispers of what this lineup could be if healthy.[1] Daulton Varsho has found his stroke too, three homers in the past week.[1] The pitching matchup favors neither team: Dylan Cease takes the mound for Toronto against Jacob Misiorowski, a young arm still finding his footing.[1][2] <strong>This is a series the Blue Jays must steal</strong>&mdash;not because they&rsquo;re the better team right now, but because both clubs are flailing, and the East won&rsquo;t wait for injuries to heal or losing streaks to end.",
        "updated": "Updated April 15, 2026"
      },
