      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Raptors",
        "body": "The Raptors' playoff dreams flickered out like a cheap candle in the wind Tuesday night, as they squandered a 12-point lead in the fourth and fell 118-112 to the Knicks at Scotiabank Arena&ndash;a gut-punch collapse that leaves them 4 games back of the East's final play-in spot with just three left on the slate. <strong>Scottie Barnes' season-ending ankle sprain in the third quarter</strong> turned hope to ash; the All-Star forward, averaging 23.4 points and 9.2 boards, crumpled on a drive and didn't return, thrusting Immanuel Quickley into the hero's role with 32 points on torrid 7-of-11 threes. At 38-41, Toronto's limped through a three-game skid, mired in eighth in the Atlantic and 10th in the conference&ndash;mathematically alive but clinically dead, outscored by 18 in the paint amid a rash of late-season injuries. Quickley's been a revelation since the Barnes injury clusterfuck, but can he drag this battered crew forward? Masai Ujiri's summer rebuild looms large. <strong>Watch Friday's must-win in Miami</strong>&ndash;win and pray for chaos, lose and it's golf season.",
        "updated": "Updated April 15, 2026"
      },
